  "prompt": "What does \"AAA\" mean in AAA title game?",
  "response": "In the context of a AAA title game, \"AAA\" (pronounced \"triple-A\") doesn't stand for a specific acronym. Instead, it's a classification used within the video game industry to denote games with the **highest development budgets, marketing budgets, and production values.**\n\nThink of it as the \"blockbuster\" category of video games. These games are typically developed by large, established studios and are expected to be major commercial successes.\n\nHere's a breakdown of what AAA usually implies:\n\n*   **High Budgets:** AAA games often have budgets exceeding tens of millions of dollars, and some can even reach hundreds of millions when you factor in marketing.\n*   **Large Development Teams:** Developing a AAA game requires a significant workforce, often involving hundreds of artists, programmers, designers, and other staff.\n*   **High Production Values:** These games prioritize cutting-edge graphics, sound design, and overall polish.\n*   **Extensive Marketing Campaigns:** AAA titles are heavily marketed to reach a wide audience.\n*   **Commercial Expectations:** They are expected to sell millions of copies to recoup their substantial investment and generate profit.\n\nIn essence, \"AAA\" is a marker of the scale and ambition of a video game project.",
